aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Information for Beech V35B in Elko, Nevada
The accident occurred in Elko, Nevada.
The accident occurred on September 8, 2012, at 09:30 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Beech V35B.
The defining event was landing gear not configured.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was WPR12CA415.
The aircraft registration was N1129T.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were 4 occupants with no injuries.
The pilot retracted the landing gear after takeoff.
A passenger advised the pilot that fuel was streaming from one of the fuel tank caps.
The pilot confirmed that fuel was leaking.
The pilot decided to abort the takeoff.
The pilot decided to land straight ahead.
The pilot forgot to extend the landing gear before the airplane touched down.
The airplane's bulkhead was damaged.
The pilot stated that he had not ensured that the fuel caps were secured.
The pilot stated that he should have done a final walk-around before taking off.
The pilot reported that there was no preimpact mechanical malfunction.
The pilot reported that there was no preimpact failure that would have precluded normal operation.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be the pilot's failure to extend the landing gear during the aborted takeoff.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined that the pilot's failure to perform a thorough preflight inspection contributed to the accident.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Elko, Nevada

## Date & Time: 
September 8, 2012, 09:30 Local

## Aircraft:
Beech V35B

## Defining Event:
Landing gear not configured

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
WPR12CA415

## Registration:
N1129T

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
4 None

## Analysis

The pilot had just retracted the landing gear after takeoff when he was advised by a passenger that fuel was streaming from one of the fuel tank caps. After confirming that fuel was leaking, the pilot decided to abort the takeoff and land straight ahead. Although he was able to land on the remaining runway, the pilot forgot to extend the landing gear before the airplane touched down, and the airplane's bulkhead was damaged. The pilot stated that he had not ensured that the fuel caps were secured and that he should have done a final walk-around before taking off to make sure everything was in order. The pilot reported that there was no preimpact mechanical malfunction or failure that would have precluded normal operation.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:The pilot's failure to extend the landing gear during the aborted takeoff. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's failure to perform a thorough preflight inspection.

## Findings

| | |
|-|-|
| Aircraft (general) | Not used/operated |
| Personnel issues | Forgotten action/omission - Pilot |
| Personnel issues | Preflight inspection - Pilot |
